  "opinion": "As a young woman in Bologna who’s just starting to navigate the world of science through my part-time delivery job and occasional online research, I see the gender gap in science not as a distant issue but something that affects my daily life. Growing up with a parent who has a master’s degree and another with a vocational diploma taught me early that education isn’t just about grades—it’s about opportunity and access. When I talk to my friends who are also in their early twenties, many of them share how they feel discouraged from pursuing STEM fields because they don’t see themselves reflected in the textbooks or the lab coats. I’ve noticed that even in my small community, the conversation around science often centers on men, and it’s hard to find role models who look like me. But here’s what I believe: we absolutely must address this gap, not just because it’s unfair, but because it limits the potential of the entire society. For instance, when I help my neighbor understand how to use a smartphone app for health tracking, I often realize how many women are missing out on tech because they don’t feel confident in their abilities. To fix this, we need to start at the grassroots level—like creating mentorship programs in schools where girls can meet women who’ve succeeded in science without having to wait until college. Also, workplaces should be more inclusive, not just in terms of hiring but in how they support women’s growth. I’m not saying it’s easy, but I believe that by making science feel welcoming and accessible to everyone, we can build a future where creativity and diversity drive innovation. After all, the best science isn’t just about data—it’s about people.",
